Here&#39;s the documentation of [`BufferedReader#ready()`][1]:

&gt; Tells whether this stream is ready to be read. A buffered character stream is ready if the buffer is not empty, or if the underlying character stream is ready.
&gt;
&gt; _[...]_
&gt;
&gt; **Returns**:
&gt;
&gt; True if the next `read()` is guaranteed not to block for input, false otherwise. Note that returning false does not guarantee that the next read will block.

So, this method is about whether or not the next read will block. You&#39;re trying to read the whole file in one go, which means you don&#39;t really care if the next read will block. Worse, what if the reader is not ready? Your loop will break, you&#39;ll close the file, and the code will continue on without having read the whole source.

A typical way to code what you&#39;re doing is:

```lang-java
try (var reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(&quot;/some-file.txt&quot;))) {
  String line;
  while ((line = reader.readLine()) != null) {
     System.out.println(line);
  }
}
```

Since `readLine()` is contracted to return `null` only when the end of the stream is reached.

Note of caution though. The above did not specify a charset, which means the default charset is used (see documentation for [Java 17 and before][3] and [Java 18+][4]). You can use `FileReader(String,Charset)` to specify a charset.

---

There&#39;s also the [`java.nio.file.*`][2] API that you can use to do the same thing. For example:

```lang-java
try (var stream = Files.lines(Path.of(&quot;/some-file.txt&quot;))) {
  stream.forEachOrdered(System.out::println);
}
```

The above uses the UTF-8 charset. You can use `Files#lines(Path,Charset)` to use a specific charset.

  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/18/docs/api/java.base/java/io/BufferedReader.html#ready()
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/18/docs/api/java.base/java/nio/file/package-summary.html
  [3]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/nio/charset/Charset.html#defaultCharset()
  [4]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/18/docs/api/java.base/java/nio/charset/Charset.html#defaultCharset()

